That blow was terrible; those who reversed Lee's orders assumed a frightful responsibility. It is only just to say that the trains only, when emptied, are said to have been referred to in the telegram, and no one acquainted with the brave and resolute Executive, Jefferson Davis, will believe him capable of that terrible fault. Let history decide, and place the blame where blame is due-we narrate. The trains passed through the Court House upon Sunday, April 2nd; their contents were thrown out in the streets of Richmond;
that night the same cars were hastening southward, and when Lee arrived, there was nothing.
We have a detailed statement of the events above referred to from an officer then in Richmond, who witnessed all. We would present that statement were any end to be reached. It would be useless. The facts are not denied.
